st successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William d' Argentine was born about 1190, in Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Reginald de Argentine, was 61 and his mother, Mrs. Matilda De Argentine, was 52. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Mrs. William d' Argentine."},"et":{"about 1190–":"umbes 1190–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1092–Female":"1092–Surnud","1114–Male":"1114–Surnud","1239–Female":"1239–Surnud","1130–1203":"1130–1203","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1239":"1239","1190":"1190","1203":"1203","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1114":"1114","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1140":"1140","1092":"1092","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mentmore, Buckingham, England, Great Britain":"Mentmore, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1190–":"noin 1190–Kuollut","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1092–Female":"1092–Kuollut","1114–Male":"1114–Kuollut","1239–Female":"1239–Kuollut","1130–1203":"1130–1203","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","1239":"1239","1190":"1190","1203":"1203","about 1190":"noin 1190","1114":"1114","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1140":"1140","1092":"1092","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Mentmore, Buckingham, England, Great Britain":"Mentmore, Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdist